<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[264,1323,283,950]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,466,483,509]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis.—</emphasis>
The male of the species is recognised by an abdominal scutum covering whole dorsum, a palp with long thin embolus (E) (
<figureCitation box="[878,968,524,550]" captionStart="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68" captionStartId="27.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[389,1202,334,1742]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[375,1211,326,1747]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68. Euryopis gertschi. 64, male, dorsal view; 65, female, dorsal view; 66, palpus of male, ventral view; 67, epigynum, ventral view; 68, spermathecae, dorsal view. 69 – 73. Pholcomma hirsutum. 69, male, dorsal view; 70, female, dorsal view; 71, palpus of male, ventral view; 72, epigynum, ventral view; 73, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273393/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[936,968,524,550]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="71.0">71</number>
</figureCitation>
), and a curved conductor (C) (
<figureCitation box="[273,367,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68" captionStartId="27.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[389,1202,334,1742]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[375,1211,326,1747]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68. Euryopis gertschi. 64, male, dorsal view; 65, female, dorsal view; 66, palpus of male, ventral view; 67, epigynum, ventral view; 68, spermathecae, dorsal view. 69 – 73. Pholcomma hirsutum. 69, male, dorsal view; 70, female, dorsal view; 71, palpus of male, ventral view; 72, epigynum, ventral view; 73, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273393/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[334,367,564,590]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="71.0">71</number>
</figureCitation>
). Females are characterised by a pale abdomen lacking a dorsal scutum, an epigynum with a well­sclerotized posterior epigynal margin (
<collectionCode box="[1012,1076,604,630]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/xqn4-34sv" name="Port Elizabeth Museum" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">PEM</collectionCode>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1104,1197,604,630]" captionStart="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68" captionStartId="27.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[389,1202,334,1742]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[375,1211,326,1747]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68. Euryopis gertschi. 64, male, dorsal view; 65, female, dorsal view; 66, palpus of male, ventral view; 67, epigynum, ventral view; 68, spermathecae, dorsal view. 69 – 73. Pholcomma hirsutum. 69, male, dorsal view; 70, female, dorsal view; 71, palpus of male, ventral view; 72, epigynum, ventral view; 73, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273393/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[1164,1197,604,630]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="72.0">72</number>
</figureCitation>
), complex copulatory ducts (CD), and oval spermathecae (S) (
<figureCitation box="[867,955,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68" captionStartId="27.[264,382,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[389,1202,334,1742]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[375,1211,326,1747]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 64 – 73. 64 – 68. Euryopis gertschi. 64, male, dorsal view; 65, female, dorsal view; 66, palpus of male, ventral view; 67, epigynum, ventral view; 68, spermathecae, dorsal view. 69 – 73. Pholcomma hirsutum. 69, male, dorsal view; 70, female, dorsal view; 71, palpus of male, ventral view; 72, epigynum, ventral view; 73, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273393/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[922,955,644,670]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="73.0">73</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="26.[264,1323,283,950]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,499,684,710]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Distribution.—</emphasis>
Known from Québec (present records) and Wisconsin south to Florida and Mississippi (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Levi" box="[509,649,724,750]" pageId="26" pageNumber="36" refString="Levi, H. W. (1957 b) The North American spider genera Paratheridula, Tekellina, Pholcomma and Archerius (Araneae: Theridiidae). Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 64 (2), 105 - 115." type="journal article" year="1957" yearSuffix="b">
Levi 
<number box="[570,632,724,750]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="1957.0">1957</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="26.[264,1323,283,950]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,448,764,790]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Remark.—</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kaston" box="[448,622,764,790]" pageId="26" pageNumber="36" refString="Kaston, B. J. (1948) Spiders of Connecticut. State Geological and Natural History Survey of Connecticut, Bulletin 70. First edition. 874 pp." type="book" year="1948">
Kaston (
<number box="[552,613,764,790]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="1948.0">1948</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
reported that 
<taxonomicName box="[801,939,764,789]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Pholcomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutum">
<emphasis box="[801,939,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">P. hirsutum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with forest litter, which is supported by our collection data. The distribution of the species and the records from deciduous litter suggest that the species may reach its northern limit below the conifer and boreal forests of North 
<collectingCountry box="[688,793,884,910]" name="United States of America" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">America</collectingCountry>
. This species is likely to be confused with a small 
<taxonomicName box="[335,464,924,950]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erigoninae">Erigoninae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[478,627,924,950]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Linyphiidae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
